             deposed, he saw the prisoner come out of Mr. Cave's shop, with two cheeses on his head; that he heard Mr. Cave cry out stop thief, and he helped to secure him.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17820109-32-person452">
                  Thomas
                   Astell
               <interp inst="t17820109-32-person452" type="surname" value="Astell"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17820109-32-person452" type="given" value="Thomas"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17820109-32-person452" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             deposed, he saw the prisoner come out of the shop with the cheese; that Mrs. Cave followed him out, and cried stop thief, the thief has stole my cheeses; that he brought him back to the shop.</p>
               <p>
                  <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="178201090051"></xptr>Mr. Cave described the marks on them, T.C. and a cross in the middle, said they were worth 4 d. 1/2 per pound.</p>
               <p>PRISONER's DEFENCE.</p>
               <p>I never took them out of the shop at all; a man asked me to carry them for him.</p>
               <p>Court. The circumstance of taking privately in the shop makes it a capital offence, if the value comes up to 5 s. if any person sees them taken, it is not a capital offence, if Mrs. Cave saw them taken, most undoubtedly it is not within the act of parliament.</p>

               <p>
